We reiterated our recommendations and Management committed to:
1. Require the OMA and the Inventory Committee to reconcile their records and reports in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 to come up with accurate and fairly presented PPE accounts in the FS;
2. Avail the one-time cleansing of all PPE accounts as prescribed by COA Circular No. 2020-006 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
3. Instruct the IC to conduct proper and complete physical count of all PPE of the MGC to determine the exact location, existence and actual condition of the PPE; and
4. Ensure the complete installation of the streetlights at Barangays Mauhang and Cabungahan that were already reported as part of the Other Infrastructure Assets. Otherwise, remove said assets from the PPE account and record the payments, if any, as receivables from concerned contractors and/or erring LGU officials.

We recommended that Management:
1. Strictly require the OMA and the MTO to conduct a comprehensive and regular reconciliation and effect the necessary adjustments to come up with the correct balances on both records;
2. Require the immediate investigation on the cause of the negative balance of the CLT account in the TF books and effect the necessary adjustments, if any.

We recommended that Management require the OMA to:
1. Make the necessary reconciliation and evaluation of the unidentified balances and ensure that proper disclosures and adjustments shall be drawn to address the same;
2. Consider the filing of request for write-off of those long outstanding receivables where settlement could no longer be ascertained in strict compliance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 as amended by COA Circular No. 2023-008.

We recommended that Management ensure the full utilization and prompt implementation of the remaining PPAs in the ensuing year and require the OMA to initiate the return or refund of the remaining balances to the SAs, of those fully implemented PPAs in accordance with Items 4.9 and 6.7 of COA Circular No. 94-013.
We also reiterated that Management should:
1. Evaluate thoroughly accounts with negative balances and prepare the necessary adjustments in the books to reflect the correct balances;
2. Submit promptly the required liquidation documents to the SAs to minimize or eliminate the unreconciled balances of fund transfers;
3. Re-evaluate the non-moving unexpended balances of FTs received from various SAs and thereafter return the balances to them if identifiable, or to the National Treasury; and
4. Request for write-off of balances which remain dormant/non-moving accounts following the guidelines and procedures prescribed by COA Circular No. 2023-008.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation and Management agreed to instruct the MA and the MT to prioritize the reconciliation of the Cash in Bank accounts to come up with the correct balances thereof as presented in the FS.
We also recommended and Management agreed to:
Monitor the status of outstanding checks to prevent spoilage, in accordance with Section 59 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
Secure a SB Resolution authorizing the change of purpose of LBP Account No. 0782-1110-19;
Facilitate the closure of unnecessary bank accounts in accordance with Section 29 (3), Article VI of the 1987 Philippine Constitution and other relevant laws, rules and regulations; and
Ensure that disbursements are supported with complete documentation and submit these immediately to the OMA for proper accounting of transactions.
Likewise, we recommended and the OMA agreed to:
Exert utmost effort in the retrieval of prior years’ records in order to determine the nature and composition of the unidentified book reconciling items;
Take up all valid reconciling items by preparing JEVs duly supported with proper documentation and furnish the AT with copies of the same;
Submit the necessary SDs in order to provide sufficient basis in taking up the adjustments in the books affecting the Cash in Bank accounts;
Investigate the causes of abnormal balances in the Cash in Bank accounts and make the necessary adjusting entries;
Revert the entries made for stale checks; and
Observe proper and timely recording of transactions in order to minimize book reconciling items.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the MA to evaluate thoroughly the accounts with negative balances and thereafter prepare the necessary adjustments in the books to reflect the correct balances;
Submit promptly the required liquidation documents to the SAs to minimize or eliminate the unreconciled balances of fund transfers;
Re-evaluate the accounts with undetermined purpose including dormant accounts and thereafter return the balances to the respective SAs; and
Follow strictly the terms and conditions stipulated in the written agreement/undertaking.  Otherwise, obtain written authority from the SA to utilize the fund for purpose/s other than what is provided thereof.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Evaluate thoroughly the proposed priority development PPAs to be funded under the 20% DF as to their readiness for implementation or procurement to avoid delays or non-implementation thereof;
Ensure the timely implementation of all PPAs whether funded by current or continuing appropriations;
Define clearly and completely in the AIP and in the annual budget the specific PPAs to be funded by the 20% DF and discontinue the practice of lump sum budgeting; and
Ensure the completeness and accuracy of the reports produced to provide relevant information to decision makers.

We recommended and Management agreed to strictly adhere to the relevant existing laws, rules and regulations on the utilization and disbursement of government funds by observing, among others, the following:
Strengthen the linkage between the planning and budgeting processes to optimize the utilization of resources and avoid conflicts in the implementation of priority PPAs;
Direct the BAC to comply with the requirement of RA No. 9184 that all procurement shall be undertaken in accordance with the approved APP/supplemental APP;
Instruct the Municipal Health Officer to use the latest PNF in the procurement of medicines as well as in the day-to-day clinical decision-making to achieve better health outcomes; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements are properly supported with the required documentation before payment to warrant their validity and propriety and to avoid future disallowance or suspension in audit.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendations and Management agreed to:
Exert utmost effort in retrieving the necessary documents to support the accuracy and validity of the fund transfers recorded under the Due to NGAs account;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to investigate the causes of negative balances of the Due to NGAs account, effect the necessary adjusting entries and furnish the Audit Team copies of the JEVs with complete supporting documents;
Ensure proper accounting of the utilization of fund transfers received through accurate recording of transactions and proper maintenance of SLs and supporting schedules; and
Submit the liquidation reports promptly to SAs in accordance with the terms and conditions stipulated in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) or the provisions under COA Circular No. 94-013, in case no reportorial requirements are provided in the MOA.
We also recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to observe proper classification of accounts in accordance with Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009 in order to come up with fairly presented FS.

3.5	We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the:
Acting General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant to (i) review the recorded road, highways and bridges which were closed to government equity in the prior years and subsequently record the same under the Road Network account to reflect the required percentage according to the transition provision; and (ii)  abide by the aforesaid Circular in maintaining the pertinent reports and ledgers to be able to provide reliable basis on the amounts presented in the financial statements; and;
(b) Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of the local roads together with related components and furnish the original copy of the report thereon to COA Audit team.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete and thorough inventory of all PPE owned/controlled by the Municipality;

Require the Property Officer-Designate and the Municipal Accountant - ICO to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;

Allow the appointed Municipal General Services Officer (MGSO) to perform all functions pertaining to supply and property management, once her appointment is finally approved by the Civil Service Commission;

Compel the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant - ICO and the Property Officer - Designate with complete description and cost of infrastructure, buildings and other structures; and

Require the Municipal Accountant - ICO to maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards to support GL account balances and the Property Officer - Designate to keep corresponding Property Cards for control purposes.

We reiterated our prior years’ audit recommendations that Management:

Direct the Municipal Accountant - ICO to conduct a thorough review of records to determine the validity of all reconciling items and come up with the correct balances of the Cash in Bank accounts; 

Require the Municipal Accountant - ICO to perform periodic reconciliation of the Cash in Bank accounts pursuant to Section 3.2 of COA Circular No. 96-011 and to immediately verify reconciling items to facilitate timely adjustments in the books of accounts; 

Instruct the Municipal Accountant - ICO and the Municipal Treasurer to exert utmost effort to reconcile their records on a regular basis to support the correctness of the Cash in Bank account balances in the financial statements; 

Close the bank accounts with dormant deposits amounting to ₱20,000.00 under the Trust Fund (TF) and revert the same to the General Fund (GF) or refund to the source agency (SAs), if necessary; and 

Submit timely the BRS together with the Bank Statements, debit/credit memos and supporting schedules/documents to COA for verification.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Assessor to submit a copy of the latest Assessment Roll on or before December 31 of each year containing the list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties which will serve as basis in the preparation of a Certified List of Taxpayers by the Municipal Treasurer;

Compel the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accountant - ICO the updated Certified List of Taxpayers due and collectible for a given year as basis for the setup so that the amount of RPT and SET Receivables will reflect the actual collectibles for the period;

Oblige the Municipal Treasurer to submit the Certified List of Delinquent Taxpayers as of December 31, 2018 prepared by her to the Municipal Accountant - ICO for recording in the books so that the balance of RPT/SET Receivable as of year-end will reflect the correct amount of tax collectibles from prior years; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant - ICO and Municipal Treasurer to regularly reconcile the balances of the RPT and SET Receivable accounts with the List of Taxpayers with paid/unpaid RPT dues maintained by the Municipal Treasurer to come up with accurate balances of the RPT and SET Receivable accounts; and

Establish a network between the Municipal Assessor’s Office and the MTO to enable information sharing of the Assessment Roll between the two offices.

We recommended that Management strictly comply with DBM and DILG JMC No. 2017-1, by taking into consideration the following:

Develop a concrete plan that will articulate the PPA, timeline, expected deliverables for each phase, key milestones, etc.;

Adopt strategies to maximize the utilization of the 20 per cent Development Fund and implement the PPAs within the targeted timeframe to achieve the social, economic and environmental outcomes essential in the attainment of the constitutional objective of a desired quality of life for all;

Direct the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to monitor periodically and include the status of implementation of barangay development projects in the Project Status Report and quarterly Project Monitoring Reports, respectively; and

Strengthen the management of reporting information by improving on its monitoring and evaluation capabilities and coordination among offices with the end view of producing more complete and accurate reports that are relevant in decision-making.

We recommended that Management:

Expedite the revision and submission of the 10-year Municipal Solid Waste Management (SWM) Plan to the Department of Environment and Natural Resources – Environmental Management Bureau (DENR-EMB) for final approval of the National SWM Council (NSWMC) and properly implement the same to ensure the efficient management of solid waste generated within its jurisdiction;

Strictly comply with the requirements of RA No. 9003 particularly on the efficient collection, proper transfer and transport of wastes; and efficient management of residuals and of final disposal sites and/or any other related technologies for the destruction/reuse of residuals; 

Seek hydro-geological assessment from DENR-Mines and Geosciences Bureau or from a professional geologist to evaluate the acceptability of the proposed site for Categorized Waste Disposal Facility pursuant to DENR Administrative Order No. 2001-34 and NSWMC Resolution No. 64, series of 2013 and submit immediately the Safe Closure and Rehabilitation Plan to the DENR-EMB to secure authority for the immediate closure of the open dump site at Barangay Lungib pursuant to Section 37 of RA No. 9003; 

Encourage the remaining 21 barangays to establish their own Materials Recovery Facilities (MRFs) for the collection, segregation, and recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes; provide adequate assistance in restoring the four non-functional status of barangay MRFs to functional status; and revert back the Municipal MRF to its intended purpose; and

Provide necessary training for SWM personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized.

