We recommended and the management agreed that the: 
     (a) Municipal Treasurer supervise and monitor the complete annual physical count of PPE and submit a report thereon copy furnished the Accounting Department for recording and reconciliation; 
     (b) Accountant compliance with the provision of PPSAS No. 17 on the provision of depreciation for PPE; 
     (c) Accountant patiently account for prior years’ PPE by updating and completing PPE ledger cards using the old but reliable accounting files.

3.11	We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
Municipal Development Council and Municipal Planning and Development Officer;
(i.)	to abide strictly with the guidelines in the formulation of the 20% Development Plan, otherwise, non-compliance thereto shall subject the concerned local officials to the sanction provided under the Local Government Code and under such other applicable laws;
(ii.) 	implement fully the identified development projects under the 20% DF;
Municipal Budget Officer to revert the fund for unimplemented projects which are not among those enumerated to be chargeable to 20% DF; and
the members of the BAC schedule early all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave way for their timely implementation and completion.

We recommended and the management agreed that: 
     (a) the Accountant initiate the conduct of reconciliation of the Cash- in- Bank records with the depository bank within ten (10) days from receipt of the Bank Statements and with the Treasurer’s cash records at least quarterly and regularly perform detailed analysis and review of cash accounts for all funds; 
     (b) the Treasurer to submit to the Accounting Department all paid disbursement vouchers summarized in the report of checks issued on a daily basis to ensure timely recording of disbursements in the books; 
     (c) the Accountant to verify and analyze dormant reconciling items to establish its validity and correctness to determine the appropriate action deemed necessary; 
     (d) the Treasurer and the Accountant to combine their efforts to retrieve the documents relative to the bank reconciling items by seeking the assistance of the depository bank to recapture the necessary information to support the adjustments for unresolved items in the bank reconciliation statements; and 

     (e) the Accountant to reclassify stale checks into liability so as to reflect the appropriate cash balance, equity and accounts payable as of year-end.

We recommended: 
     (a) The Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to submit written explanation for the amount of ₱1,184,423.49 which was inappropriately charged to 20% Development Fund; 
     (b) That the Local Chief Executive and other concerned officials exercise prudence in the processing of transactions/payments to ensure proper charging; 
     (c) Municipal Accountant to stop the practice of allowing administrative and regular expenditures against 20% Development Fund and fully adhere to the provisions of DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1;  

     (d)instruct Municipal Planning and Development Officer and Municipal Engineer to properly evaluate the technical viability of the Programs/Projects/Activities included in the Local Development Plan and not to include those PPAs with technical problems; 
     (e) direct the BAC to strictly comply with the approved schedule of all procurement activities pertaining to development projects to pave the way for their timely implementation and completion; and 
     (f) ensure that the Municipal Planning and Development Officer and Municipal Engineer regularly monitor the status of project implementation so that necessary interventions may be introduced at the earliest time.

We recommended and the management agreed that the GAD Focal person: 
     (a) analyze properly a particular activity for an accurate timeline attainable; 
     (b) prepare preliminaries of PPAs to be included in the GAD Plan so that those PPAs that cannot be executed during the year will not be included and; 
     (c) explain/justify in writing her failure to implement the PPAs included in the GAD Plan needed by the poor.

We recommended and the management agreed that Members of the Provincial Local School Board: 
     (a) prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute; 
     (b) request for inputs from the Deped official/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the Deped criteria and with due regard to the provisions of R.A. No. 5447, Sections 100 and 272, RA 7160 and Deped-DBM-DILG Joint Circular prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund; 
     (c) maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the Project Program Activities (PPA’s), and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprograming, if necessary.

We recommended the management to: 
     (a) instruct the GS Officer to determine and accomplish Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) containing all obsolete and unserviceable property of the Province; 
     (b) require GS Officer and PEP Officer to adopt adequate measures to safeguard and preserve unserviceable properties and to keep proper records for motor vehicle specifically those that pertain to ownership which is a requisite in disposal or transfer of agency’s assets; 
     (c) cause the disposal committee to perform appropriate action on disposing the unserviceable property; 
     (d) require the Municipal Accountant to employ conscious and prudent efforts to provide proper records for all fixed assets of the auditee such as subsidiary ledger and ledger cards for property, plant and equipment in anticipation for book adjustment of disposed assets and reclassify all obsolete and unserviceable property into Other Assets for proper presentation in the financial statement.
